Part 1: Understanding Task Creation and Status UpdatesMy 


Initial Understanding
Given the names of the files and the project structure, I believed there would be some kind of class to create and modify tasks, and to save the data. I thought that the application would be asked for a command by the user, it would process it, create or update a task and store it.

Files Involved

The key files used with the creation and updating of tasks are:

TaskManagerCli.java – Handles commands entered by the user, such as create and status.
TaskManager.java – The main logic for creating Tasks and updating the status of Tasks.
Task.java – It is a java class that represents a task and has properties such as title, description, priority, status, due date, tags etc.
TaskStorage.java – Represents a collection of tasks to be stored, retrieved, modified and saved in the file tasks.json.


How Task Creation Works:

When a user creates a task, the flow is:

User enters create command
          ↓
TaskManagerCli receives the command
          ↓
TaskManager creates a new Task object
          ↓
TaskStorage stores the task
          ↓
Task is saved into tasks.json

TaskManagerCli class is used to receive the information typed by the user and to pass it to TaskManager. The TaskManager creates a new Task object. New tasks have a default status of TODO and automatically get a unique ID, a creation date. Then it is passed to TaskStorage, which then stores it in the tasks.json file.



How Task Status Update Works:

When a user changes the status of a task, the flow is:

User enters status command
          ↓
TaskManagerCli receives the command
          ↓
TaskManager finds the task
          ↓
Task status is updated
          ↓
Changes are saved to tasks.json

TaskStorage returns the required task to the TaskManager which updates the TaskManager's status. The model marks the application as DONE at runtime, by calling markAsDone() if the new status is "DONE". If you update after that, the changes will be saved, and will be available the next time you run the application.


The different ways that data can be stored and retrieved:

The application saves task information to a file, tasks.json.

The TaskStorage class is responsible for handling this data. Loads existing tasks at launch and saves changes when tasks are created, updated, or deleted.

Tasks are temporarily stored in memory in a HashMap with a taskId as the key for fast retrieval of a specific task.



