Part 3: Mapping Data Flow and State Management

My Current Understanding
I can guess that in the Task Manager application, data is initiated with a command the user enters. Information is passed to the CLI, to the TaskManager, and then stored or retrieved via TaskStorage.

The main files involved in this data flow are:

TaskManagerCli.java – accepts user input and command.
TaskManager.java – Handles the input of the commands and manages the operations of the tasks.
Task.java – contains the information and functionality of a task.
TaskStorage.java – handles loading/saving tasks from tasks.json file.


Data Flow Example: Creating a Task

The flow of creating a task is:

User enters create command
          ↓
TaskManagerCli reads the command and information
          ↓
TaskManager creates a new Task object
          ↓
TaskStorage adds the task to memory
          ↓
TaskStorage saves the task into tasks.json




How changes in the state are handled.

Within the application, the tasks are stored in a HashMap within TaskStorage. The task ID provides a quick and easy way to locate a specific task.

If a task is modified – e.g. status or priority is changed – the following occurs:
The task is picked up from TaskStorage.
Changes are made to the Task object that is required.
The changes are saved back into tasks.json.

This implies that the most up-to-date version of the task is saved even after the program is closed.



Data Transformations
-The main transformations occurring to the data are:
-Command line user input is translated into task information.
-Text-based dates will be converted to LocalDateTime objects.
-When saving, Java task objects are converted to JSON format.
-When loading the application, you'll get Java objects back from JSON data.


These are some possible areas for failure.
As I was looking around the code, I saw that there were some potential problems that could arise:

-The user can provide incorrect date format.
-The user can submit a task ID that isn't found.
-May have issues reading or writing to the tasks.json file.
-An invalid priority or status value can be entered by a user.

The application tries to catch some of these cases, and displays an error message and prevents the wrong changes.




How to Debug Data Flow Troubleshooting
If a task wasn't being created or updated properly, I would follow the flow of the data by checking the following:

-If TaskManagerCli has been given the proper user input.
-If the request was handled properly by TaskManager.
-Whether TaskStorage successfully saved and loaded the task.
-Whether or not the data was properly added to tasks.json.



